# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: server-sent-events
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] The use of Comet techniques in web development predates the use of the word *Comet* as a neologism for the collective techniques.
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] Comet is known by several other names, including *Ajax Push*, *Reverse Ajax*, *Two-way-web*, *HTTP Streaming*, and *HTTP server push* among others.
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] The term *Comet* is not an acronym, but was coined by Alex Russell in his 2006 blog post.
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] In recent years, the standardisation and widespread support of WebSocket and Server-sent events has rendered the Comet model obsolete.
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] The ability to embed Java applets into browsers (starting with Netscape Navigator 2.0 in March 1996) made two-way sustained communications possible, using a raw TCP socket to communicate between the browser and the server.
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] This socket can remain open as long as the browser is at the document hosting the applet.
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] Event notifications can be sent in any format – text or binary – and decoded by the applet.
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] The very first application using browser-to-browser communications was Tango Interactive, implemented in 1996–98 at the Northeast Parallel Architectures Center (NPAC) at Syracuse University using DARPA funding.
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] TANGO architecture has been patented by Syracuse University.
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] TANGO framework has been extensively used as a distance education tool.
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] The framework has been commercialized by CollabWorx and used in a dozen or so Command&Control and Training applications in the United States Department of Defense.
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] The first set of Comet implementations dates back to 2000, with the Pushlets, Lightstreamer, and KnowNow projects.
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] Pushlets, a framework created by Just van den Broecke, was one of the first open source implementations.
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] Pushlets were based on server-side Java servlets, and a client-side JavaScript library.
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] Bang Networks – a Silicon Valley start-up backed by Netscape co-founder Marc Andreessen – had a lavishly financed attempt to create a real-time push standard for the entire web.
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] In April 2001, Chip Morningstar began developing a Java-based (J2SE) web server which used two HTTP sockets to keep open two communications channels between the custom HTTP server he designed and a client designed by Douglas Crockford; a functioning demo system existed as of June 2001.
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] The server and client used a messaging format that the founders of State Software, Inc. assented to coin as JSON following Crockford's suggestion.
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] The entire system, the client libraries, the messaging format known as JSON and the server, became the State Application Framework, parts of which were sold and used by Sun Microsystems, Amazon.com, EDS and Volkswagen.
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] In March 2006, software engineer Alex Russell coined the term Comet in a post on his personal blog.
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] The new term was a play on Ajax (Ajax and Comet both being common household cleaners in the USA).
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] New Comet variants were created, such as the Java-based ICEfaces JSF framework (although they prefer the term "*Ajax Push*").
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] Others that had previously used Java-applet based transports switched instead to pure-JavaScript implementations.
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] Comet applications attempt to eliminate the limitations of the page-by-page web model and traditional polling by offering two-way sustained interaction, using a persistent or long-lasting HTTP connection between the server and the client.
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] Since browsers and proxies are not designed with server events in mind, several techniques to achieve this have been developed, each with different benefits and drawbacks.
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] The biggest hurdle is the HTTP 1.1 specification, which states "this specification... encourages clients to be conservative when opening multiple connections".
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] Therefore, holding one connection open for real-time events has a negative impact on browser usability: the browser may be blocked from sending a new request while waiting for the results of a previous request, e.g., a series of images.
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] This can be worked around by creating a distinct hostname for real-time information, which is an alias for the same physical server.
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] This strategy is an application of domain sharding.
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] Specific methods of implementing Comet fall into two major categories: streaming and long polling.
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] An application using streaming Comet opens a single persistent connection from the client browser to the server for all Comet events.
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] These events are incrementally handled and interpreted on the client side every time the server sends a new event, with neither side closing the connection.
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] A basic technique for dynamic web application is to use a hidden iframe HTML element (an *inline frame*, which allows a website to embed one HTML document inside another).
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] This invisible iframe is sent as a chunked block, which implicitly declares it as infinitely long (sometimes called "forever frame").
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] As events occur, the iframe is gradually filled with `script` tags, containing JavaScript to be executed in the browser.
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] Because browsers render HTML pages incrementally, each `script` tag is executed as it is received.
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] Some browsers require a specific minimum document size before parsing and execution is started, which can be obtained by initially sending 1–2 kB of padding spaces.
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] One benefit of the iframes method is that it works in every common browser.
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] Two downsides of this technique are the lack of a reliable error handling method, and the impossibility of tracking the state of the request calling process.
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] None of the above streaming transports work across all modern browsers without negative side-effects.
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] This forces Comet developers to implement several complex streaming transports, switching between them depending on the browser.
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] Consequently, many Comet applications use long polling, which is easier to implement on the browser side, and works, at minimum, in every browser that supports XHR.
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] As the name suggests, long polling requires the client to poll the server for an event (or set of events).
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] The browser makes an Ajax-style request to the server, which is kept open until the server has new data to send to the browser, which is sent to the browser in a complete response.
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] The browser initiates a new long polling request in order to obtain subsequent events.
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] IETF RFC 6202 "Known Issues and Best Practices for the Use of Long Polling and Streaming in Bidirectional HTTP" compares long polling and HTTP streaming.
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] For the most part, XMLHttpRequest long polling works like any standard use of XHR.
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] The browser makes an asynchronous request of the server, which may wait for data to be available before responding.
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] The response can contain encoded data (typically XML or JSON) or Javascript to be executed by the client.
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] At the end of the processing of the response, the browser creates and sends another XHR, to await the next event.
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] Thus the browser always keeps a request outstanding with the server, to be answered as each event occurs.
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] While any Comet transport can be made to work across subdomains, none of the above transports can be used across different second-level domains (SLDs), due to browser security policies designed to prevent cross-site scripting attacks.
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] That is, if the main web page is served from one SLD, and the Comet server is located at another SLD (which does not have cross-origin resource sharing enabled), Comet events cannot be used to modify the HTML and DOM of the main page, using those transports.
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] This problem can be sidestepped by creating a proxy server in front of one or both sources, making them appear to originate from the same domain.
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] However, this is often undesirable for complexity or performance reasons.
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] Unlike iframes or XMLHttpRequest objects, `script` tags can be pointed at any URI, and JavaScript code in the response will be executed in the current HTML document.
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] This creates a potential security risk for both servers involved, though the risk to the data provider (in our case, the Comet server) can be avoided using JSONP.
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] A long-polling Comet transport can be created by dynamically creating `script` elements, and setting their source to the location of the Comet server, which then sends back JavaScript (or JSONP) with some event as its payload.
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] Each time the script request is completed, the browser opens a new one, just as in the XHR long polling case.
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] This method has the advantage of being cross-browser while still allowing cross-domain implementations.
[src:server-sent-events/comet-programming] Browser-native technologies are inherent in the term Comet.
[src:server-sent-events/event-driven-programming] In computer programming, **event-driven programming** is a programming paradigm in which the flow of the program is determined by external events.
[src:server-sent-events/event-driven-programming] User interface (UI) events from keyboards and mice, touchpads and touchscreens, and external sensor inputs are common cases.
[src:server-sent-events/event-driven-programming] Events may also be programmatically generated, such as from messages from other programs, notifications from other threads, or other network events.
[src:server-sent-events/event-driven-programming] Event-driven programming is the dominant paradigm used in graphical user interface (GUI) applications and network servers.
[src:server-sent-events/event-driven-programming] In an event-driven application, there is generally an event loop that listens for events and then triggers a callback function when one of those events is detected.
[src:server-sent-events/event-driven-programming] Event-driven programs can be written in any programming language, although the task is easier in languages that provide high-level abstractions.
[src:server-sent-events/event-driven-programming] Although they do not exactly fit the event-driven model, interrupt handling and exception handling have many similarities.
[src:server-sent-events/event-driven-programming] It is important to differentiate between event-driven and message-driven (aka queue-driven) paradigms: event-driven services (e.g.
[src:server-sent-events/event-driven-programming] AWS SNS) are decoupled from their consumers, whereas message/queue-driven services (e.g.
[src:server-sent-events/event-driven-programming] AWS SQS) are coupled with their consumers.
[src:server-sent-events/event-driven-programming] Because the event loop that retrieves and dispatches events is common amongst applications, many programming frameworks provide an implementation of an event loop, and the application developer only needs to write the event handlers.
[src:server-sent-events/event-driven-programming] The actual logic is contained in event handler routines.
[src:server-sent-events/event-driven-programming] These routines handle the events to which the main program will respond.
[src:server-sent-events/event-driven-programming] For example, a single mouse-click on a "Save" command button in a GUI program might trigger a routine to save data to a database.
[src:server-sent-events/event-driven-programming] An "Exit" button might trigger a routine to exit the program.
[src:server-sent-events/event-driven-programming] The event loop receives events from all such command buttons and other GUI elements, dispatching the appropriate event handler routine for each button.
[src:server-sent-events/event-driven-programming] Event handler routines need to be bound to specific events, so the event loop can dispatch the correct routine in response to the event.
[src:server-sent-events/event-driven-programming] Many IDEs simplify this process by providing the programmer with an event handling template for each specific event (such as a button click), allowing the programmer to focus on writing the event-handling code.
[src:server-sent-events/event-driven-programming] In a sequential program, keeping track of execution order and history is normally trivial.
[src:server-sent-events/event-driven-programming] But in an event-driven program, event handlers execute non-sequentially in response to external events.
[src:server-sent-events/event-driven-programming] Special attention and planning is required to correctly structure the event handlers to work when called in any order.
[src:server-sent-events/event-driven-programming] Most existing GUI architectures use event-driven programming.
[src:server-sent-events/event-driven-programming] The Java AWT framework processes all UI changes on a single thread, called the Event dispatching thread.
[src:server-sent-events/event-driven-programming] Similarly, all UI updates in the Java framework JavaFX occur on the JavaFX Application Thread.
[src:server-sent-events/event-driven-programming] Most network servers and frameworks such as Node.js are also event-driven.
[src:server-sent-events/http] HTTP is a request–response protocol in the client–server model.
[src:server-sent-events/http] A transaction starts with a client submitting a request to the server, the server attempts to satisfy the request and returns a response to the client that describes the disposition of the request and optionally contains a requested resource such as an HTML document or other content.
[src:server-sent-events/http] In a common scenario, a web browser acts as the client, and a web server, hosting one or more websites, is the server.
[src:server-sent-events/http] A web browser is an example of a user agent (UA).
[src:server-sent-events/http] Other types of user agent include the indexing software used by search providers (web crawlers), voice browsers, mobile apps, and other software that accesses, consumes, or displays web content.
[src:server-sent-events/http] HTTP is designed to permit intermediate network elements to improve or enable communications between clients and servers.
[src:server-sent-events/http] High-traffic websites often benefit from web cache servers that deliver content on behalf of upstream servers to improve response time.
[src:server-sent-events/http] Web browsers cache previously accessed web resources and reuse them, whenever possible, to reduce network traffic.
[src:server-sent-events/http] HTTP proxy servers at private network boundaries can facilitate communication for clients without a globally routable address, by relaying messages with external servers.
[src:server-sent-events/http] To allow intermediate HTTP nodes (proxy servers, web caches, etc.) to accomplish their functions, some of the HTTP headers (found in HTTP requests/responses) are managed hop-by-hop whereas other HTTP headers are managed end-to-end (managed only by the source client and by the target web server).
[src:server-sent-events/http] A web resource is located by a uniform resource locator (URL), using the Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) schemes *http* and *https*.
[src:server-sent-events/http] URIs are encoded as hyperlinks in HTML documents, so as to form interlinked hypertext documents.
[src:server-sent-events/http] The protocol has been revised over time.
[src:server-sent-events/http] A version is identified as HTTP/# where # is the version number.
[src:server-sent-events/http] This article covers aspects of all versions but provides primary coverage for HTTP/0.9, HTTP/1.0, and HTTP/1.1.
[src:server-sent-events/http] Separate articles cover HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 in detail.
[src:server-sent-events/http] In HTTP/1.0, a separate TCP connection to the same server is made for every resource request.
[src:server-sent-events/http] In HTTP/1.1, instead a TCP connection can be reused to make multiple resource requests (i.e. of HTML pages, frames, images, scripts, stylesheets, etc.).
[src:server-sent-events/http] HTTP/1.1 communications therefore experience less latency as the establishment of TCP connections presents considerable overhead, especially under high traffic conditions.
[src:server-sent-events/http] Enhancements added with HTTP/2 allow for less latency and, in most cases, higher speeds than HTTP/1.1 communications.
[src:server-sent-events/http] HTTP/3 uses QUIC + UDP transport protocols instead of TCP.
[src:server-sent-events/http] Only the IP layer is used (which UDP, like TCP, builds on).
[src:server-sent-events/http] This slightly improves the average speed of communications and avoids the occasional problem of TCP connection congestion that can temporarily block or slow down the data flow of all its streams (another form of "*head of line blocking*").
[src:server-sent-events/http] HTTP/2 is supported by 71% of websites (34.1% HTTP/2 + 36.9% HTTP/3 with backwards compatibility) and supported by almost all web browsers (over 98% of users).
[src:server-sent-events/http] It is also supported by major web servers over Transport Layer Security (TLS) using an Application-Layer Protocol Negotiation (ALPN) extension where TLS 1.2 or newer is required.
[src:server-sent-events/http] HTTP/3 is used on 36.9% of websites and is supported by most web browsers, i.e.
[src:server-sent-events/http] (at least partially) supported by 97% of users.
[src:server-sent-events/http] HTTP/3 uses QUIC instead of TCP for the underlying transport protocol.
[src:server-sent-events/http] Like HTTP/2, it does not obsolete previous major versions of the protocol.
[src:server-sent-events/http] In 2019, support for HTTP/3 was first added to Cloudflare and Chrome and also enabled in Firefox.
[src:server-sent-events/http] HTTP/3 has lower latency for real-world web pages and loads faster than HTTP/2, in some cases over three times faster than HTTP/1.1, which is still commonly the only protocol enabled.
[src:server-sent-events/http] HTTPS, the secure variant of HTTP, is used by more than 85% of websites.
[src:server-sent-events/http] HTTP presumes an underlying and reliable transport layer protocol.
[src:server-sent-events/http] The standard choice of the underlying protocol prior to HTTP/3 is Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:server-sent-events/http] HTTP/3 uses a different transport layer called QUIC, which provides reliability on top of the unreliable User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:server-sent-events/http] HTTP/1.1 and earlier have been adapted to be used over plain unreliable UDP in multicast and unicast situations, forming HTTPMU and HTTPU.
[src:server-sent-events/http] They are used in UPnP and Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP), two protocols usually run on a local area network.
[src:server-sent-events/http] HTTP is a stateless application-level protocol and it requires a reliable network transport connection to exchange data between client and server.
[src:server-sent-events/http] In HTTP implementations, TCP/IP connections are used using well-known ports (typically port 80 if the connection is unencrypted or port 443 if the connection is encrypted, see also List of TCP and UDP port numbers).
[src:server-sent-events/http] In HTTP/2, a TCP/IP connection plus multiple protocol channels are used.
[src:server-sent-events/http] In HTTP/3, the application transport protocol QUIC over UDP is used.
[src:server-sent-events/http] Data is exchanged through a sequence of request–response messages which are exchanged by a session layer transport connection.
[src:server-sent-events/http] An HTTP client initially tries to establish a connection, real or virtual, with a server.
[src:server-sent-events/http] An HTTP server listening on the port accepts the connection and then waits for a client's request message.
[src:server-sent-events/http] The client sends its HTTP request message.
[src:server-sent-events/http] Upon receiving the request the server sends back an HTTP response message, which includes header(s) plus a body if it is required.
[src:server-sent-events/http] The body of this response message is typically the requested resource, although an error message or other information may also be returned.
[src:server-sent-events/http] At any time and for many reasons, either the client or server can close the connection.
[src:server-sent-events/http] Closing a connection is usually advertised by one or more HTTP headers in the last request or response.
[src:server-sent-events/http] In HTTP/0.9, the TCP/IP connection is always closed after server response has been sent, so it is never persistent.
[src:server-sent-events/http] In HTTP/1.0, the TCP/IP connection should always be closed by server after a response has been sent.
[src:server-sent-events/http] In HTTP/1.1, a keep-alive-mechanism was officially introduced so that a connection could be reused for more than one request/response.
[src:server-sent-events/http] Such persistent connections reduce request latency perceptibly because the client does not need to re-negotiate the TCP 3-Way-Handshake connection after the first request has been sent.
[src:server-sent-events/http] Another positive side effect is that, in general, the connection becomes faster with time due to TCP's slow-start-mechanism.
[src:server-sent-events/http] HTTP/1.1 added also HTTP pipelining in order to further reduce lag time when using persistent connections by allowing clients to send multiple requests before waiting for each response.
[src:server-sent-events/http] Because of this, only HEAD and some GET requests (i.e. limited to real file requests and so with URLs without query string used as a command, etc.) could be pipelined in a safe and idempotent mode.
[src:server-sent-events/http] After many years of struggling with the problems introduced by enabling pipelining, this feature was first disabled and then removed from most browsers.
[src:server-sent-events/http] Pipelining was also removed because of the announced adoption of HTTP/2.
[src:server-sent-events/http] HTTP/2 extended the usage of persistent connections by multiplexing many concurrent requests/responses through a single TCP/IP connection.
[src:server-sent-events/http] HTTP/3 does not use TCP/IP connections but QUIC + UDP.
[src:server-sent-events/http] In HTTP/0.9, a requested resource was always sent in its entirety.
[src:server-sent-events/http] HTTP/1.0 added headers to manage resources cached by a client in order to allow conditional GET requests.
[src:server-sent-events/http] As a stateless protocol, HTTP does not require the web server to retain information or status about each user for the duration of multiple requests.
[src:server-sent-events/http] If a web application needs an application session, it implements it via HTTP cookies, hidden variables in a web form or another mechanism.
[src:server-sent-events/http] Typically, to start a session, an interactive login is performed, and to end a session, a logout is requested by the user.
[src:server-sent-events/http] These kind of operations use a custom authentication mechanism, not HTTP authentication.
[src:server-sent-events/http] HTTP provides multiple authentication schemes such as basic access authentication and digest access authentication which operate via a challenge–response mechanism whereby the server identifies and issues a challenge before serving the requested content.
[src:server-sent-events/http] HTTP provides a general framework for access control and authentication, via an extensible set of challenge–response authentication schemes, which can be used by a server to challenge a client request and by a client to provide authentication information.
[src:server-sent-events/http] The authentication mechanisms described above belong to the HTTP protocol and are managed by client and server HTTP software (if configured to require authentication before allowing client access to one or more web resources), and not by the web applications using an application session.
[src:server-sent-events/http] The HTTP authentication specification includes realms that provide an arbitrary, implementation-specific construct for further dividing resources common to a given root URI.
[src:server-sent-events/http] The realm value string, if present, is combined with the canonical root URI to form the protection space component of the challenge.
[src:server-sent-events/http] This in effect allows the server to define separate authentication scopes under one root URI.
[src:server-sent-events/http] The most popular way of establishing an encrypted HTTP connection is HTTPS.
[src:server-sent-events/http] Two other methods for establishing an encrypted HTTP connection also exist: Secure Hypertext Transfer Protocol, and using the HTTP/1.1 Upgrade header to specify an upgrade to TLS.
[src:server-sent-events/http] Browser support for these two is, however, nearly non-existent.
[src:server-sent-events/http] This section describes messages for HTTP/1.1.
[src:server-sent-events/http] Later versions, HTTP/2 and HTTP/3, use a binary protocol, where headers are encoded in a single `HEADERS` and zero or more `CONTINUATION` frames using HPACK (HTTP/2) or QPACK (HTTP/3), which both provide efficient header compression.
[src:server-sent-events/http] The request or response line from HTTP/1 has also been replaced by several pseudo-header fields, each beginning with a colon (`:`).
[src:server-sent-events/http] At the highest level, a message consists of a header followed by a body.
[src:server-sent-events/http] A header consists of lines of ASCII text; each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:server-sent-events/http] Structured data that differs for request vs. response.
[src:server-sent-events/http] lines (at least 1 for HTTP/1.1); see below.
[src:server-sent-events/http] A body consists of data in any format; not limited to ASCII.
[src:server-sent-events/http] The format must match that specified by the `Content-Type` header field if the message contains one.
[src:server-sent-events/http] A body is optional or, in other words, can be blank.
[src:server-sent-events/http] Before HTTP/2, the term *entity* was used to mean the body plus header fields that describe the body.
[src:server-sent-events/http] In particular, not all headers were considered part of the entity.
[src:server-sent-events/http] The term *entity header* referred to a header that was considered part of the entity, and sometimes the body was called the *entity body*.
[src:server-sent-events/http] Modern documentation uses *body* and *header* without using *entity*.
[src:server-sent-events/http] A header field represents metadata about the containing message.
[src:server-sent-events/http] Generally, the information of a header field is used by software and not shown to the user.
[src:server-sent-events/http] A header field line is formatted as a name-value pair with a colon separator.
[src:server-sent-events/http] Whitespace is not allowed around the name, but leading and trailing whitespace is ignored for the value part.
[src:server-sent-events/http] Unlike a method name that must match exactly (case-sensitive), a header field name is matched ignoring case although often shown with each word capitalized.
[src:server-sent-events/http] For example, the following are header fields for `Host` and `Accept-Language`.
[src:server-sent-events/http] The standards do not limit the size of a header field or the number of fields in a message.
[src:server-sent-events/http] However, most servers, clients, and proxy software impose limits for practical and security reasons.
[src:server-sent-events/http] For example, the Apache 2.3 server by default limits the size of each field to 8190 bytes, and there can be at most 100 header fields in a single request.
[src:server-sent-events/http] Although deprecated by RFC 7230, in the past, long lines could be split into multiple lines with a continuation line starting with a space or tab character.
[src:server-sent-events/http] A request is sent by a client to a server.
[src:server-sent-events/http] The start line includes a method name, a request URI and the protocol version with a single space between each field.
[src:server-sent-events/http] Request header fields allow the client to pass additional information beyond the request line, acting as request modifiers (similarly to the parameters of a procedure).
[src:server-sent-events/http] They give information about the client, about the target resource, or about the expected handling of the request.
[src:server-sent-events/http] In the HTTP/1.1 protocol, all header fields except `Host` are optional.
[src:server-sent-events/http] A request line containing only the path name is accepted by servers to maintain compatibility with HTTP clients before the HTTP/1.0 specification in RFC 1945.
[src:server-sent-events/http] The protocol structures transaction as operating on resources.
[src:server-sent-events/http] What a resource represents, whether pre-existing data or data that is generated dynamically, depends on the implementation of the server.
[src:server-sent-events/http] Often, the resource corresponds to a file or the output of an executable running on the server.
[src:server-sent-events/http] A request identifies a method (sometimes informally called *verb*) to classify the desired action to be performed on a resource.
[src:server-sent-events/http] The HTTP/1.0 specification defined the GET, HEAD, and POST methods as well as listing the PUT, DELETE, LINK and UNLINK methods under additional methods.
[src:server-sent-events/http] However, the HTTP/1.1 specification added five new methods: PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, and TRACE.
[src:server-sent-events/http] Any client can use any method and the server can be configured to support any combination of methods.
[src:server-sent-events/http] If a method is unknown to an intermediate, it will be treated as an unsafe and non-idempotent method.
[src:server-sent-events/http] There is no limit to the number of methods that can be defined, which allows for future methods to be specified without breaking existing infrastructure.
[src:server-sent-events/http] For example, WebDAV defined seven new methods and RFC 5789 specified the PATCH method.
[src:server-sent-events/http] A general-purpose web server is required to implement at least GET and HEAD, and all other methods are considered optional by the specification.
[src:server-sent-events/http] This is in contrast to HTTP header field names which are case-insensitive.
[src:server-sent-events/http] The request is for a representation of a resource.
[src:server-sent-events/http] include the representation data in the body.
[src:server-sent-events/http] in the response header, without having to transfer the entire representation.
[src:server-sent-events/http] The request is to process a resource in some way.
[src:server-sent-events/http] The request is to create or update a resource with the state in the request.
[src:server-sent-events/http] A distinction from POST is that the client specifies the target location on the server.
[src:server-sent-events/http] to the origin server identified by the request target.
[src:server-sent-events/http] Request is for a report of the HTTP methods that are supported for a resource.
[src:server-sent-events/http] This can be used to check the functionality of a web server by requesting '*' instead of a specific resource.
[src:server-sent-events/http] Requests the server to respond with the received request in the response body.
[src:server-sent-events/http] That way a client can see what (if any) changes or additions have been made by intermediaries.
[src:server-sent-events/http] The request is to modify a resource according to its partial state in the request.
[src:server-sent-events/http] Compared to PUT, this can save bandwidth by sending only part of a resource's representation instead of all of it.
[src:server-sent-events/http] A request method is *safe* if a request with that method has no intended effect on the server.
[src:server-sent-events/http] The methods GET, HEAD, OPTIONS, and TRACE are defined as safe.
[src:server-sent-events/http] In other words, safe methods are intended to be read-only.
[src:server-sent-events/http] Safe methods can still have side effects not seen by the client, such as appending request information to a log file or charging an advertising account.
[src:server-sent-events/http] In contrast, the methods POST, PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, and PATCH are not safe.
[src:server-sent-events/http] They may modify the state of the server or have other effects such as sending an email.
[src:server-sent-events/http] Such methods are therefore not usually used by conforming web robots or web crawlers; some that do not conform tend to make requests without regard to context or consequences.
[src:server-sent-events/http] Despite the prescribed safety of GET requests, in practice their handling by the server is not technically limited in any way.
[src:server-sent-events/http] Careless or deliberately irregular programming can allow GET requests to cause non-trivial changes on the server.
[src:server-sent-events/http] This is discouraged because of the problems which can occur when web caching, search engines, and other automated agents make unintended changes on the server.
[src:server-sent-events/http] For example, a website might allow deletion of a resource through a URL such as *https://example.com/article/1234/delete*, which, if arbitrarily fetched, even using GET, would simply delete the article.
[src:server-sent-events/http] A properly coded website would require a DELETE or POST method for this action, which non-malicious bots would not make.
[src:server-sent-events/http] One example of this occurring in practice was during the short-lived Google Web Accelerator beta, which prefetched arbitrary URLs on the page a user was viewing, causing records to be automatically altered or deleted *en masse*.
[src:server-sent-events/http] The beta was suspended only weeks after its first release, following widespread criticism.
[src:server-sent-events/http] A request method is *idempotent* if multiple identical requests with that method have the same effect as a single such request.
[src:server-sent-events/http] The methods PUT and DELETE, and safe methods are defined as idempotent.
[src:server-sent-events/http] Safe methods are trivially idempotent, since they are intended to have no effect on the server whatsoever; the PUT and DELETE methods, meanwhile, are idempotent since successive identical requests will be ignored.
[src:server-sent-events/http] A website might, for instance, set up a PUT endpoint to modify a user's recorded email address.
[src:server-sent-events/http] If this endpoint is configured correctly, any requests which ask to change a user's email address to the same email address which is already recorded—e.g. duplicate requests following a successful request—will have no effect.
[src:server-sent-events/http] Similarly, a request to DELETE a certain user will have no effect if that user has already been deleted.
[src:server-sent-events/http] In contrast, the methods POST, CONNECT, and PATCH are not necessarily idempotent, and therefore sending an identical POST request multiple times may further modify the state of the server or have further effects, such as sending multiple emails.
[src:server-sent-events/http] In some cases this is the desired effect, but in other cases it may occur accidentally.
[src:server-sent-events/http] A user might, for example, inadvertently send multiple POST requests by clicking a button again if they were not given clear feedback that the first click was being processed.
[src:server-sent-events/http] While web browsers may show alert dialog boxes to warn users in some cases where reloading a page may re-submit a POST request, it is generally up to the web application to handle cases where a POST request should not be submitted more than once.
[src:server-sent-events/http] Note that whether or not a method is idempotent is not enforced by the protocol or web server.
[src:server-sent-events/http] It is perfectly possible to write a web application in which (for example) a database insert or other non-idempotent action is triggered by a GET or other request.
[src:server-sent-events/http] To do so against recommendations, however, may result in undesirable consequences, if a user agent assumes that repeating the same request is safe when it is not.
[src:server-sent-events/http] A request method is *cacheable* if responses to requests with that method may be stored for future reuse.
[src:server-sent-events/http] The methods GET, HEAD, and POST are defined as cacheable.
[src:server-sent-events/http] In contrast, the methods PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, TRACE, and PATCH are not cacheable.
[src:server-sent-events/http] A response is sent to the client by the server.
[src:server-sent-events/http] The start line of a response consists of the protocol version, a status code and optionally a reason phrase with fields separated by a single space character.
[src:server-sent-events/http] The following response start line specifies protocol version `HTTP/1.1`, status code `400` and reason phrase `Bad Request`.
[src:server-sent-events/http] Response header fields allow the server to pass additional information beyond the status line, acting as response modifiers.
[src:server-sent-events/http] They give information about the server or about further access to the target resource or related resources.
[src:server-sent-events/http] Each response header field has a defined meaning which can be further refined by the semantics of the request method or response status code.
[src:server-sent-events/http] The status code is a three-digit, decimal, integer value that represents the disposition of the server's attempt to satisfy the client's request.
[src:server-sent-events/http] Generally, a client handles a response primarily based on the status code and secondarily on response header fields.
[src:server-sent-events/http] A client may not understand each status code that a server reports but it must understand the class as indicated by the first digit and treat an unrecognized code as equivalent to the x00 code of that class.
[src:server-sent-events/http] The request was received, continuing process.
[src:server-sent-events/http] The request was successfully received, understood, and accepted.
[src:server-sent-events/http] Further action needs to be taken in order to complete the request.
[src:server-sent-events/http] The request cannot be fulfilled due to an issue that the client might be able to control.
[src:server-sent-events/http] The server failed to fulfill an apparently valid request.
[src:server-sent-events/http] The standard reason phrases are only recommendations.
[src:server-sent-events/http] A web server is allowed to use a localized equivalent.
[src:server-sent-events/http] If a status code indicates a problem, the user agent might display the reason phrase to the user to provide further information about the nature of the problem.
[src:server-sent-events/http] The standard also allows the user agent to attempt to interpret the reason phrase, though this might be unwise since the standard explicitly specifies that status codes are machine-readable and reason phrases are human-readable.
[src:server-sent-events/http] The following demonstrates an HTTP/1.1 request-response transaction for a server at www.example.com, port 80.
[src:server-sent-events/http] HTTP/1.0 would use the same messages except for a few missing headers.
[src:server-sent-events/http] HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 would use the same request-response mechanism but with different representations for HTTP headers.
[src:server-sent-events/http] The following is a request with no body.
[src:server-sent-events/http] It consists of a start line, 6 header fields and a blank line – each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:server-sent-events/http] The `Host` header field distinguishes between various DNS names sharing a single IP address, allowing name-based virtual hosting.
[src:server-sent-events/http] While optional in HTTP/1.0, it is mandatory in HTTP/1.1.
[src:server-sent-events/http] Although not clear in the representation above (due to limitations of this wiki), the blank line at the end results in ending in two line terminator sequences.
[src:server-sent-events/http] Represented as a stream of characters, a shorted version of above shows this more clearly with `<CRLF>` representing a line terminator sequence: `GET / HTTP/1.1<CRLF>Host: www.example.com<CRLF><CRLF>`.
[src:server-sent-events/http] In the following response, the ETag (entity tag) header field is used to determine if a cached version of the requested resource is identical to the current version of the resource on the server.
[src:server-sent-events/http] The `Content-Type` header field specifies the Internet media type of the data conveyed by the HTTP message, and `Content-Length` indicates its length in bytes.
[src:server-sent-events/http] The HTTP/1.1 webserver publishes its ability to respond to requests for a byte range of the resource by including `Accept-Ranges: bytes`.
[src:server-sent-events/http] This is useful, if the client needs to have only certain portions of a resource sent by the server, which is called byte serving.
[src:server-sent-events/http] When `Connection: close` is sent, it means that the web server will close the TCP connection immediately after the end of the transfer of this response.
[src:server-sent-events/http] Most of the header fields are optional but some are mandatory.
[src:server-sent-events/http] When header `Content-Length` is missing from a response with a body, then this should be considered an error in HTTP/1.0 but it may not be an error in HTTP/1.1 if header `Transfer-Encoding: chunked` is present.
[src:server-sent-events/http] Chunked transfer encoding uses a chunk size of 0 to mark the end of the content.
[src:server-sent-events/http] Some old implementations of HTTP/1.0 omitted the header `Content-Length` when the length of the body was not known at the beginning of the response and so the transfer of data to client continued until server closed the socket.
[src:server-sent-events/http] `Content-Encoding: gzip` informs the client that the body is compressed per the gzip algorithm.
[src:server-sent-events/http] A content delivery protocol that was displaced by HTTP in the early 1990s.
[src:server-sent-events/http] A Gopher-inspired protocol which mandates privacy-related features.
[src:server-sent-events/http] Tim Berners-Lee and his team at CERN are credited with inventing HTTP, along with HTML and the associated technology for a web server and a client user interface called web browser.
[src:server-sent-events/http] Berners-Lee designed HTTP in order to help with the adoption of his other idea: the "WorldWideWeb" project, which was first proposed in 1989, now known as the World Wide Web.
[src:server-sent-events/http] Development of HTTP was initiated in 1989 and summarized in a simple document describing the behavior of a client and a server using the first HTTP version, named 0.9.
[src:server-sent-events/http] That version was subsequently developed, eventually becoming the public 1.0.
[src:server-sent-events/http] Development of early HTTP Request for Comments (RFC) documents started a few years later in a coordinated effort by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) and the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C), with work later moving to the IETF.
[src:server-sent-events/http] The protocol used had only one method, namely GET, which would request a page from a server.
[src:server-sent-events/http] The response from the server was always an HTML page.
[src:server-sent-events/http] Since 1992, a new document was written to specify the evolution of the basic protocol towards its next full version.
[src:server-sent-events/http] It supported both the simple request method of the 0.9 version and the full GET request that included the client HTTP version.
[src:server-sent-events/http] This was the first of the many unofficial HTTP/1.0 drafts that preceded the final work on HTTP/1.0.
[src:server-sent-events/http] The HTTP WG planned to revise and publish new versions of the protocol as HTTP/1.0 and HTTP/1.1 within 1995, but, because of the many revisions, that timeline lasted much more than one year.
[src:server-sent-events/http] The HTTP WG planned also to specify a far future version of HTTP called HTTP-NG (HTTP Next Generation) that would have solved all remaining problems, of previous versions, related to performances, low latency responses, etc. but this work started only a few years later and it was never completed.
[src:server-sent-events/http] In May 1996, RFC 1945 was published as a final HTTP/1.0 revision of what had been used in previous 4 years as a pre-standard HTTP/1.0-draft which was already used by many web browsers and web servers.
[src:server-sent-events/http] In early 1996 developers started to even include unofficial extensions of the HTTP/1.0 protocol (i.e. keep-alive connections, etc.) into their products by using drafts of the upcoming HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:server-sent-events/http] Since early 1996, major web browsers and web server developers also started to implement new features specified by pre-standard HTTP/1.1 drafts specifications.
[src:server-sent-events/http] End-user adoption of the new versions of browsers and servers was rapid.
[src:server-sent-events/http] In March 1996, one web hosting company reported that over 40% of browsers in use on the Internet used the new HTTP/1.1 header "Host" to enable virtual hosting, and that by June 1996, 65% of all browsers accessing their servers were pre-standard HTTP/1.1 compliant.
[src:server-sent-events/http] In January 1997, RFC 2068 was officially released as HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:server-sent-events/http] In June 1999, RFC 2616 was released to include all improvements and updates based on previous (obsolete) HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:server-sent-events/http] Resuming the old 1995 plan of previous HTTP Working Group, in 1997 an *HTTP-NG Working Group* was formed to develop a new HTTP protocol named HTTP-NG (HTTP New Generation).
[src:server-sent-events/http] A few proposals / drafts were produced for the new protocol to use multiplexing of HTTP transactions inside a single TCP/IP connection, but in 1999, the group stopped its activity passing the technical problems to IETF.
[src:server-sent-events/http] In 2007, the IETF HTTP Working Group (HTTP WG bis or HTTPbis) was restarted firstly to revise and clarify previous HTTP/1.1 specifications and secondly to write and refine future HTTP/2 specifications (named httpbis).
[src:server-sent-events/http] In 2009, Google announced SPDY – a binary protocol they developed to speed up web traffic between browsers and servers.
[src:server-sent-events/http] In many tests, using SPDY was indeed faster than using HTTP/1.1.
[src:server-sent-events/http] SPDY was integrated into Google's Chromium and then into other major web browsers.
[src:server-sent-events/http] Some of the ideas about multiplexing HTTP streams over a single TCP connection were taken from various sources, including the work of W3C HTTP-NG Working Group.
[src:server-sent-events/http] In 2012, HTTP Working Group (HTTPbis) announced the need for a new protocol; initially considering aspects of SPDY and eventually deciding to derive the new protocol from SPDY.
[src:server-sent-events/http] In May 2015, HTTP/2 was published as RFC 7540.
[src:server-sent-events/http] The protocol was quickly adopted by web browsers already supporting SPDY and more slowly by web servers.
[src:server-sent-events/http] As of 2022, HTTP/0.9 support has not been officially, completely deprecated and is still present in many web servers and browsers (for server responses only), even if usually disabled.
[src:server-sent-events/http] It is unclear how long it will take to decommission HTTP/0.9.
[src:server-sent-events/http] In 2020, the first drafts of HTTP/3 were published and major web browsers and web servers started to adopt it.
[src:server-sent-events/http] On 6 June 2022, IETF standardized HTTP/3 as RFC 9114.
[src:server-sent-events/http] In June 2022, RFC documents were published that deprecated many of the previous documents and introducing a few minor changes and a refactoring of HTTP semantics description into a separate document.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] In push technology, clients can express their preferences for certain types of information or data, typically through a process known as the publish–subscribe model.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] In this model, a client "subscribes" to specific information channels hosted by a server.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] When new content becomes available on these channels, the server automatically sends, or "pushes," this information to the subscribed client.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] Under certain conditions, such as restrictive security policies that block incoming HTTP requests, push technology is sometimes simulated using a technique called polling.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] In these cases, the client periodically checks with the server to see if new information is available, rather than receiving automatic updates.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] Synchronous conferencing and instant messaging are examples of push services.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] Chat messages and sometimes files are pushed to the user as soon as they are received by the messaging service.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] Both decentralized peer-to-peer programs (such as WASTE) and centralized programs (such as IRC or XMPP) allow pushing files, which means the sender initiates the data transfer rather than the recipient.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] Email may also be a push system: SMTP is a push protocol (see Push e-mail).
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] However, the last step—from mail server to desktop computer—typically uses a pull protocol like POP3 or IMAP.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] Modern e-mail clients make this step seem instantaneous by repeatedly polling the mail server, frequently checking it for new mail.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] The IMAP protocol includes the IDLE command, which allows the server to tell the client when new messages arrive.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] The original BlackBerry was the first popular example of push-email in a wireless context.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] Another example is the PointCast Network, which was widely covered in the 1990s.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] It delivered news and stock market data as a screensaver.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] Both Netscape and Microsoft integrated push technology through the Channel Definition Format (CDF) into their software at the height of the browser wars, but it was never very popular.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] Other uses of push-enabled web applications include software updates distribution ("push updates"), market data distribution (stock tickers), online chat/messaging systems (webchat), auctions, online betting and gaming, sport results, monitoring consoles, and sensor network monitoring.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] The Web push proposal of the Internet Engineering Task Force is a simple protocol using HTTP version 2 to deliver real-time events, such as incoming calls or messages, which can be delivered (or "pushed") in a timely fashion.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] The protocol consolidates all real-time events into a single session which ensures more efficient use of network and radio resources.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] A single service consolidates all events, distributing those events to applications as they arrive.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] This requires just one session, avoiding duplicated overhead costs.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] Web Notifications are part of the W3C standard and define an API for end-user notifications.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] A notification allows alerting the user of an event, such as the delivery of an email, outside the context of a web page.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] As part of this standard, Push API is fully implemented in Chrome, Firefox, and Edge, and partially implemented in Safari as of February 2023.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] HTTP server push (also known as HTTP streaming) is a mechanism for sending unsolicited (asynchronous) data from a web server to a web browser.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] HTTP server push can be achieved through any of several mechanisms.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] As a part of HTML5 the Web Socket API allows a web server and client to communicate over a full-duplex TCP connection.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] Generally, the web server does not terminate a connection after response data has been served to a client.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] The web server leaves the connection open so that if an event occurs (for example, a change in internal data which needs to be reported to one or multiple clients), it can be sent out immediately; otherwise, the event would have to be queued until the client's next request is received.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] Most web servers offer this functionality via CGI (e.g., Non-Parsed Headers scripts on Apache HTTP Server).
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] The underlying mechanism for this approach is chunked transfer encoding.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] Another mechanism is related to a special MIME type called `multipart/x-mixed-replace`, which was introduced by Netscape in 1995.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] Web browsers interpret this as a document that changes whenever the server pushes a new version to the client.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] It is still supported by Firefox, Opera, and Safari today, but it is ignored by Internet Explorer and is only partially supported by Chrome.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] It can be applied to HTML documents, and also for streaming images in webcam applications.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] The WHATWG Web Applications 1.0 proposal includes a mechanism to push content to the client.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] On September 1, 2006, the Opera web browser implemented this new experimental system in a feature called "Server-Sent Events".
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] In this technique, the server takes advantage of persistent HTTP connections, leaving the response perpetually "open" (i.e., the server never terminates the response), effectively fooling the browser to remain in "loading" mode after the initial page load could be considered complete.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] The server then periodically sends snippets of JavaScript to update the content of the page, thereby achieving push capability.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] By using this technique, the client doesn't need Java applets or other plug-ins in order to keep an open connection to the server; the client is automatically notified about new events, pushed by the server.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] One serious drawback to this method, however, is the lack of control the server has over the browser timing out; a page refresh is always necessary if a timeout occurs on the browser end.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] Long polling is itself not a true push; long polling is a variation of the traditional polling technique, but it allows emulating a push mechanism under circumstances where a real push is not possible, such as sites with security policies that require rejection of incoming HTTP requests.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] With long polling, the client requests to get more information from the server exactly as in normal polling, but with the expectation that the server may not respond immediately.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] If the server has no new information for the client when the poll is received, then instead of sending an empty response, the server holds the request open and waits for response information to become available.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] Once it does have new information, the server immediately sends an HTTP response to the client, completing the open HTTP request.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] Upon receipt of the server response, the client often immediately issues another server request.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] In this way the usual response latency (the time between when the information first becomes available and the next client request) otherwise associated with polling clients is eliminated.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] This technique, used by chat applications, makes use of the XML Socket object in a single-pixel Adobe Flash movie.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] Under the control of JavaScript, the client establishes a TCP connection to a unidirectional relay on the server.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] The relay server does not read anything from this socket; instead, it immediately sends the client a unique identifier.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] Next, the client makes an HTTP request to the web server, including this identifier with it.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] The web application can then push messages addressed to the client to a local interface of the relay server, which relays them over the Flash socket.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] The advantage of this approach is that it appreciates the natural read-write asymmetry that is typical of many web applications, including chat, and as a consequence it offers high efficiency.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] Since it does not accept data on outgoing sockets, the relay server does not need to poll outgoing TCP connections *at all*, making it possible to hold open tens of thousands of concurrent connections.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] In this model, the limit to scale is the TCP stack of the underlying server operating system.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] In services such as cloud computing, to increase reliability and availability of data, it is usually pushed (replicated) to several machines.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] For example, the Hadoop Distributed File System (HDFS) makes 2 extra copies of any object stored.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] RGDD focuses on efficiently casting an object from one location to many while saving bandwidth by sending minimal number of copies (only one in the best case) of the object over any link across the network.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] For example, Datacast is a scheme for delivery to many nodes inside data centers that relies on regular and structured topologies and DCCast is a similar approach for delivery across data centers.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] A push notification is a message that is "pushed" from a back-end server or application to a user interface, e.g. mobile applications or desktop applications.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] Apple introduced push notifications for iPhone in 2009, and in 2010 Google released "Google Cloud to Device Messaging" (superseded by Google Cloud Messaging and then by Firebase Cloud Messaging).
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] Push notifications are mainly divided into two approaches, local notifications and remote notifications.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] For local notifications, the application schedules the notification with the local device's OS.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] The application sets a timer in the application itself, provided it is able to continuously run in the background.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] When the event's scheduled time is reached, or the event's programmed condition is met, the message is displayed in the application's user interface.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] Remote notifications are handled by a remote server.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] Under this scenario, the client application needs to be registered on the server with a unique key (e.g., a UUID or Apple *Device Token*).
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] The server then transmits the message against the unique key to deliver it to the client via an agreed client/server protocol such as HTTP or XMPP.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] When the push notification arrives at the client, it can cause the display of short notifications or messages, set badges on application icons, blink or continuously light up the notification LED, or play alert sounds to attract user's attention.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] Push notifications are usually used by applications to bring information to users' attention.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] Real-time push notifications may raise privacy issues since they can be used to bind virtual identities of social network pseudonyms to the real identities of the smartphone owners.
[src:server-sent-events/long-polling] The use of unnecessary push notifications for promotional purposes has been criticized as an example of attention theft.
[src:server-sent-events/server-sent-events] All modern browsers support server-sent events: Firefox 6+, Google Chrome 6+, Opera 11.5+, Safari 5+, Microsoft Edge 79+, Brave.
[src:server-sent-events/server-sent-events] Since SSE does not use either persistent connections nor chunked transfer encoding, HTTP/1.1 is not a technical requirement.
[src:server-sent-events/server-sent-events] The SSE mechanism was first specified by Ian Hickson as part of the "WHATWG Web Applications 1.0" proposal starting in 2004.
[src:server-sent-events/server-sent-events] In September 2006, the Opera web browser implemented the experimental technology in a feature called "Server-Sent Events".
[src:server-sent-events/server-sent-events] The W3C published Server-Sent Events as a Recommendation on February 3, 2015, after years of development through Working Drafts and Candidate Recommendations.
[src:server-sent-events/server-sent-events] When sending high-frequency data , the server must manage backpressure to prevent saturating clients.
